{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_013LcpjLXbBW2hmWWmJnpm67","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze this document analysis system with three independent AI reviewers. This is a classic AI/ML pipeline problem where I need to carefully consider:\n\n1. What could fail in the real system?\n2. What level of infrastructure would catch those failures?\n3. Would mocks hide these failures?\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n## Behavior 1: Clause Extractor Identifies Key Terms\n\nThe clause extractor needs to identify parties, dates, obligations, penalties in a contract.\n\n**Possible failures:**\n- The LLM doesn't extract certain clause types even when present\n- The extraction logic misses edge cases (embedded dates, multi-party agreements, etc.)\n- The formatted output is malformed\n- The extraction response parsing fails\n\n**Can a mock hide this?**\nYes! A mock that returns `[\"party1\", \"date1\", \"obligation1\", \"penalty1\"]` would always pass. But the real LLM might:\n- Miss \"penalty1\" if it's phrased indirectly\n- Return a malformed response that breaks parsing\n- Refuse to analyze certain clause types\n- Return inconsistent formats\n\n**Why Integration minimum?**\nBecause you need:\n- A real or realistic contract document\n- The actual extraction logic to run\n- The response parsing to work\n- However, you could still mock the LLM call itself\n\nBut wait... the behavior says \"identifies all key terms... present in the contract.\" This is about correctness of extraction from the LLM's perspective. If the LLM is the source of truth about what terms are present, then you need to test against what the real LLM would produce, not a mock.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The behavior is: \"identifies all key terms present in the contract.\" The real failure mode is: the system fails to extract terms that are actually in the contract. This depends on:\n1. The LLM's ability to understand the contract (non-deterministic, model-dependent)\n2. The parsing/formatting of the extraction response\n\nFor #2, you could mock the LLM and test parsing. \n\nThe parsing and formatting can be validated with mocked responses, but determining whether the extraction is truly complete requires the actual model. The core question is what \"all key terms\" means—if it's measured against human judgment or a gold standard, I need real model output to evaluate completeness. This pushes it to **Agentic** level because the correctness claim depends on the LLM's actual performance, and mocking would mask incomplete extractions that only surface with real model behavior. is \"present\" — there's an implicit ground truth about what should be extracted. I could test this with a gold-standard dataset of annotated contracts, mocking the LLM to return those extractions, then verifying the system formats and preserves them correctly. That would be Integration level.\n\nBut the realistic failure modes are what matter: the LLM outputs something the system doesn't capture, or returns malformed data that breaks parsing. Both require either actual LLM calls or highly realistic mocks to catch. The correctness ultimately hinges on real LLM behavior, so this lands at Agentic.\n\nLooking at confidence: Unit testing can't handle this (0%), Integration with mocks might catch some issues but misses LLM edge cases (20%), System and Workflow don't apply here (10% each). Agentic testing with real LLM calls is needed to verify the system actually identifies all terms (60%).\n\nThe core question is what \"identifies all key terms\" means in practice. Take a contract stating \"This agreement between Alice and Bob dated January 1, 2025 states that Alice will pay $10,000 if obligations are not met.\" A proper extraction should surface Parties, Dates, Obligations, and Penalties. The real test is whether the system captures everything the LLM can extract from varied contract structures.\n\nTwo approaches exist: mocking the LLM with known extractions to verify the system handles them correctly (Integration level), or using a real LLM to see if it can extract terms and the system properly captures those results (Agentic level). The distinction matters—mocking catches when the system loses information between LLM output and final report, while real LLM testing catches when the LLM itself struggles with certain clause types. Since the behavior requires identifying all key terms across the full pipeline, I need the real LLM approach.\n\nThough there's ambiguity: if the behavior only asks whether the system preserves what the LLM extracts, mocking with realistic responses would suffice. The safest bet is Agentic testing as the minimum, though solid mocking could work too. Looking at confidence levels—Unit at 0.05, Integration at 0.30, System at 0.05, Agentic at 0.55, Workflow at 0.05—the real issue is identifying the failure boundary: when the LLM outputs certain extractions but the system reports different ones, that's a preservation failure I need to catch.\n\nThe distinction matters: if the LLM simply fails to extract something because it misunderstands the contract language, that's a capability issue requiring real LLM responses. Since the behavior specifies \"identifies all key terms... present in the contract,\" both extraction quality and system handling matter. Agentic testing is the realistic minimum, though Integration with well-designed mock data could catch most system-level issues. My confidence distribution shifts to Unit 0.05, Integration 0.25, System 0.05, Agentic 0.60, Workflow 0.05.\n\nFor the risk assessor behavior, the challenge is detecting indirect or euphemistic language that violates policy—not just obvious violations. The system could fail by missing flagged items, misapplying the policy, or the LLM not recognizing subtle problematic phrasing.\n\nThe core difficulty is semantic understanding. A phrase like \"the party may choose to discontinue engagement at their discretion\" might constitute a problematic opt-out clause depending on the risk policy, but only a real LLM grasps this nuance. A mock could easily hide failures by returning \"no risks found\" on happy paths while the actual LLM either misses indirect risks, misinterprets the policy, or flags false positives. Since the failure boundary centers on whether the LLM can detect indirect/euphemistic risk language, this is fundamentally a capability question requiring Agentic-level testing.\n\nYou could approach this at Integration level with a dataset of contracts containing both direct and indirect problematic language, mocking the LLM to return correct flags, and verifying the system preserves and formats them properly. However, truly validating detection of indirect or euphemistic risks demands a real LLM.\n\nThe distribution reflects this: Unit testing covers policy logic (0.05), Integration handles mock risks on realistic documents (0.20), System testing isn't relevant (0.05), Agentic testing with a real LLM dominates at 0.65, and Workflow testing is minimal (0.05).\n\nFor the compliance checker, the core challenge is whether the contract satisfies all applicable regulatory requirements for a given jurisdiction. This requires knowing which requirements apply, understanding the contract text, and performing the actual compliance check—with the second part being the hardest since it depends entirely on LLM comprehension. A mock could trivially claim compliance, making Agentic testing essential to catch genuine misunderstandings of jurisdiction-specific requirements.\n\nAt Integration level, you'd use contracts with known compliance status for specific jurisdictions and mock the LLM responses, testing that results are preserved correctly. But validating true compliance verification requires a real LLM analyzing actual contracts against real regulatory requirements. The distribution is Unit (0.05), Integration (0.20), System (0.10—regulatory requirements might come from external sources, though \"configured jurisdiction\" suggests internal configuration), Agentic (0.60), and Workflow (0.05).\n\nThe merge step is fundamentally about preserving conflicting assessments with proper attribution when reviewers disagree—for instance, when the extractor flags something as \"standard\" but the risk assessor marks it \"high risk.\" Failures here include losing one assessment, losing attribution, selecting one assessment and discarding others, or corrupting the output format. This is primarily about merge logic rather than LLM behavior, since the LLMs produce outputs that the merge step then combines.\n\nAt Integration, you can mock the three reviewers to generate conflicting outputs and verify the merge preserves both with correct attribution. The core behavior is testable there with good mocking, though realistic conflicts might require real LLM outputs. The distribution is Unit (0.10), Integration (0.65), System (0.10), and Agentic (0.15).\n\nFor the full pipeline, the key risk is that one reviewer's findings get lost during collection or merging. You'd test by mocking all three reviewers, running them concurrently, and verifying the unified report contains all findings without duplication or loss.\n\nThe orchestration layer—dispatching to three reviewers, collecting their results, and merging them—requires testing at the System level because it involves concurrent execution, timeout handling, and error propagation. A single reviewer crashing shouldn't break the entire pipeline, and slow responses need proper timeout management. You'd need realistic LLM execution or at least semi-realistic conditions to validate that all three calls complete, results get collected even if one is delayed, and concurrent operations don't lose data.\n\nThe question becomes whether this is primarily a System concern or an Agentic one. If the failure is about orchestration and coordination—ensuring parallel steps don't interfere with each other—that's System-level. But if the focus is on how real LLM calls behave in a multi-step pipeline, that leans Agentic. Workflow could apply if viewing this as a full pipeline with parallel agentic steps, though the task definition emphasizes sequential steps. The distribution might be: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.15, System 0.30, Agentic 0.35, Workflow 0.15—with the core question being whether the failure boundary is about orchestration or about realistic LLM behavior in a pipeline. what could go wrong?\" perspective:\n\n**Behavior 1: Clause Extractor Identifies All Key Terms**\n\nReal failure modes include LLM hallucinations, missing terms due to unusual phrasing, response parsing failures, system truncation, and LLM refusals. Mocks can only catch parsing and formatting issues—they can't expose the real LLM behaviors like hallucinations or policy misunderstandings. This requires actual LLM calls, pointing toward **Agentic** level testing.\n\n**Behavior 2: Risk Assessor Flags Indirect/Euphemistic Risks**\n\nThe risk assessor needs to handle cases where the LLM misinterprets indirect language or applies risk policies inconsistently with the system's intent. These are behavioral gaps that mocks won't reveal.\n\n**Behavior 3: Compliance Checker Verifies Requirements**\n\nSimilar pattern emerges—misunderstandings of regulatory requirements, incomplete contract analysis, and hallucinated compliance can't be caught by mocks. Real LLM execution is essential.\n\n**Behavior 4: Merge Preserves Conflicting Assessments**\n\nThis is pure logic testing. Merge operations, attribution preservation, and conflict handling are deterministic and fully mockable at the **Integration** level.\n\n**Behavior 5: Full Pipeline Completes Correctly**\n\nPipeline integrity depends on realistic concurrency and timing. Race conditions and timeout cascades require **System** or **Agentic** testing with actual concurrent execution, not just mocked delays.\n\nFor the clause extractor, I need **Agentic** testing—sending real contracts to verify comprehensive extraction of parties, dates, obligations, and penalties without truncation. For the risk assessor, **Agentic** is also required to catch euphemistic language like \"may discontinue at discretion\" that mocks would miss. The compliance checker similarly needs real LLM execution to validate regulatory understanding and prevent hallucinated compliance claims. The merge logic itself can stay at **Integration** since it's deterministic, but the full pipeline requires **System** or **Agentic** level testing to surface concurrency issues and timeout failures. that Workflow? I think it might be. The task involves three steps running in parallel rather than sequentially, which could make it System-level due to the concurrent execution infrastructure needed. I'll classify it as System minimum, though Agentic or Workflow are defensible alternatives. Testing requires running the full pipeline with a real contract to verify concurrent execution of all three reviewers, collection of results within timeout, and the merge step receiving complete findings without data loss. The consistency check is partial since there's ambiguity around whether parallel execution fits the Workflow definition of \"multiple agentic steps in sequence.\"\n\nFor behavior 5, I need to reconsider the classification. The definitions distinguish between System (subprocess, OS behavior, real HTTP, or external API calls), Agentic (depends on real LLM non-determinism or AI/ML model calls), and Workflow (multiple agentic steps in sequence or full agent pipeline). Since this involves three concurrent steps rather than sequential ones, the minimum level depends on whether the infrastructure for parallel execution or the LLM calls themselves are the primary testing concern. a full pipeline with three independent reviewers feeding into a merge step, this is fundamentally a Workflow test—you're validating that the entire agentic pipeline executes correctly end-to-end and produces a unified report without losing any individual findings. You could test the orchestration logic at a lower level with mocked reviewers, but the actual behavior being validated here requires real LLM calls to ensure the pipeline handles genuine conflicts and nuances across all three perspectives. The failure boundary hinges on whether the issue stems from merge logic errors, race conditions in concurrent execution, real LLM outputs diverging from expectations, or the entire pipeline failing end-to-end. Since the behavior explicitly requires \"completes correctly for a real contract,\" Workflow testing is the appropriate minimum level.\n\nNow I'll assign probabilities for each behavior. For the Clause Extractor, Unit testing can't validate \"identifies all\" without actual LLM capabilities, so it's minimal at 0.05. Integration with mocked LLMs might catch some issues but risks missing what a real model would extract, placing it at 0.20. System testing isn't relevant here at 0.05. Agentic testing becomes critical at 0.65 since verifying \"identifies all key terms\" requires real LLM behavior. Workflow is lower at 0.05 since this is a single component, not a multi-step pipeline.\n\nFor the Risk Assessor, Unit and Integration remain similarly constrained—0.05 and 0.15 respectively—though Integration could test with mocked LLMs against curated problematic language examples. - Test: End-to-end with real LLM calls, verify all steps execute in parallel and handle timeouts\n   - Would it pass at System? Might miss orchestration issues\n   - Would it catch real failures? Only at Workflow level\n   - Plan consistent: True\n\nNow I can structure the output with confidence that each behavior's test level matches its actual requirements. \"Real contract\" likely refers to a realistic document rather than requiring actual LLM calls. I could test this at System level by using a genuine contract, mocking the three reviewers to return findings, and verifying the dispatch, collection, and merge logic preserves all results. That would cover the orchestration without needing real LLM non-determinism. So System might actually be sufficient here—the minimum level depends on whether the test truly requires agentic behavior or just realistic inputs with mocked external components. Workflow is the right level since this is explicitly a full agent pipeline with multiple sequential agentic steps—the clause extractor, risk assessor, and compliance checker all run before merging results. You can test this effectively with mocked LLM responses to verify the orchestration works correctly, so System-level testing with mocks would catch the core issues, but Workflow testing ensures the full pipeline integrates properly.\n\nLooking at each test against its chosen level: the clause extractor and risk assessor both genuinely need real LLM calls to detect actual clause types and euphemistic language, making Agentic the right fit. The compliance checker similarly requires real LLM reasoning to understand jurisdiction-specific requirements. For the merge step, Integration testing with mocked outputs from the three reviewers makes sense—it validates that conflicting assessments are both preserved when the merge logic processes them, though you could test the merge function in isolation if it's pure logic.\n\nThe full pipeline test is the critical one. It explicitly calls for running with a real contract and verifying concurrent execution of all three reviewers with timeout handling and complete result collection. That's clearly Workflow-level work—orchestrating multiple agentic components together. Even though you could theoretically mock the LLMs and run it at System level, the test description's emphasis on \"real contract\" and concurrent execution points to needing actual workflow orchestration.\n\nNow I'll structure the final output with these five behaviors and their test specifications.\n\nFor the clause extractor, the minimum level is Agentic because real failures emerge when the LLM encounters unusual phrasing or misses terms entirely. Mocking would mask these issues—you need actual LLM calls to surface extraction failures that matter in production.\n\nFor the risk assessor, it needs to flag problematic language according to the configured policy, including indirect or euphemistic phrasing that could slip past simpler pattern matching.\n\nThe minimum level is Agentic because detecting nuanced risk language requires genuine LLM understanding—a mock would just return hardcoded flags and miss the real challenge. For instance, phrases like \"may choose to discontinue engagement at their discretion\" or \"reasonable efforts\" need semantic comprehension to identify as policy violations. Testing involves running the assessor against contracts with both explicit and subtle risk language across different policies, confirming it catches both types with appropriate severity and reasoning, and that all flagged items retain their supporting context.\n\nFor the compliance checker, the minimum level is also Agentic since correctness hinges on the LLM grasping both contract content and jurisdiction-specific rules. A mock returning \"compliant=true\" would pass trivially, but real failures emerge when the LLM misunderstands requirements or overlooks compliance gaps. Testing requires running the checker across jurisdictions like GDPR, HIPAA, and general commercial law, using contracts that both satisfy and violate requirements, then verifying it identifies gaps with explanations (e.g., \"missing data retention policy for GDPR\") and preserves the determination with supporting evidence.\n\nThe merge step combines two review outputs with conflicting assessments on the same clause while maintaining attribution. This is Integration-level because the risk lies in merge logic itself—incorrectly selecting one assessment over another or losing attribution—not in LLM capability. Mocked reviewer outputs with deliberate conflicts can thoroughly test this. The test uses outputs where extraction labels a clause \"standard payment term,\" risk assessment flags it \"high risk\" due to late payment penalties, and compliance checking deems it \"acceptable under jurisdiction X.\" After merging, the report should contain all three assessments with clear attribution and no loss or scrambling of information, tested across multiple scenarios.\n\nThe full pipeline requires Workflow-level testing because it involves dispatching to all three reviewers, collecting results concurrently, and merging findings into a unified report. The critical failure mode is losing findings from one reviewer or data loss during concurrent execution. While orchestration logic could be tested at System level with mocked LLMs, ensuring the pipeline works end-to-end realistically demands testing with actual agentic steps—confirming all three reviewers execute, results are collected within timeout, and merge receives everything intact. The test executes the pipeline on a realistic legal contract, verifying concurrent dispatch of all three reviewers, collection of all results, and that the merge step receives complete outputs from each reviewer.\n\nThe test should also vary contract complexity to ensure no findings are lost during orchestration or merge, and include error scenarios like reviewer timeouts to validate graceful degradation or retry logic.\n\n- Plan Consistent: true\n- Level Probabilities: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.10, System 0.20, Agentic 0.25, Workflow 0.40","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12688,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12688},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2191b094-ad30-4e52-b0ed-f8ec89980080","uuid":"b4055cde-a655-48ee-9079-